"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 32–34
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2chronicles-32-34.py

Ch 32: Hezekiah vs. Sennacherib — Emmanuel principle (v8); Hezekiah's illness types Christ's
       solidarity with human weakness (Heb 4:15); divine test of the heart (v31); Hezekiah's
       pride-then-humility arc contrasted with Christ's perfect self-humbling (Phil 2:6-8).
Ch 33: Manasseh — the greatest sinner who repented (vv11-13); the abomination in the temple
       (v7 → Matt 24:15); Gehenna's origin (v6); the Prodigal Son parallel in the repentance
       narrative; Amon's refusal to humble himself as the negative counterpart.
Ch 34: Josiah — young king seeking God (v3 → Luke 2:41-52); temple cleansing (vv4-7 → John 2);
       Book of the Law found (v14) as the recovered Word pointing to the Word made flesh;
       Huldah's oracle on personal mercy within corporate judgment (vv26-28); covenant renewal
       (v31) with full heart as the Shema fulfilled in Christ.

Key decisions:
- 33:7 "abomination": linked to Dan 9:27/Matt 24:15 trajectory as shadow
- 33:11-13 Manasseh's repentance: typed as Prodigal Son pattern (Luke 15)
- 34:14 Book of the Law discovery: shadow pointing to Word made flesh (John 1:14)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2 = {
  "32": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;After these acts of faithfulness, Sennacherib king of Assyria came and invaded Judah.&rdquo; The sequence is deliberate: covenant faithfulness does not remove trial &mdash; it determines how the trial is faced and resolved. As a theme, this pattern runs from Abraham (tested after his call) through Job, through the wilderness generation, and reaches its definitive expression in Christ&rsquo;s temptation immediately after his baptismal commissioning (Matt 4:1). The testing of the faithful is not an exception to God&rsquo;s care but an instrument of it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Hezekiah sees Sennacherib&rsquo;s intention and takes action. The perception of threat and the measured response is the responsible exercise of human agency within divine sovereignty. As a theme, the wise king who correctly discerns the enemy&rsquo;s intention anticipates Christ, who &ldquo;knew what was in man&rdquo; (John 2:25) and who sees through every form of opposition to its spiritual root.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Hezekiah consults his officials about stopping water supplies before the siege. As a theme, the prudent use of counsel and practical wisdom is not at odds with faith in YHWH &mdash; it is the embodiment of it. The NT wisdom tradition (Jas 1:5) calls for the same: asking God for wisdom and then acting wisely in the world. Christ perfectly unites divine wisdom with practical action (1 Cor 1:24: &ldquo;Christ the power of God and the wisdom of God&rdquo;).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The stopping of the water sources denies the enemy a vital resource. As a theme, the identification and strategic withdrawal of what sustains life from the enemy&rsquo;s reach anticipates the NT warfare language: &ldquo;Do not give the devil a foothold&rdquo; (Eph 4:27). The spiritual warfare of the new covenant is fought with wisdom and preparation, grounded in the power of Christ.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Hezekiah rebuilds the broken walls and strengthens the city&rsquo;s defenses. As a shadow, the faithful king repairing the breach in the city of God anticipates Nehemiah&rsquo;s wall-building as an image of restoration. More directly, it points to Christ as the one who repairs the ultimate breach &mdash; the broken relationship between humanity and God &mdash; restoring the wall of salvation: &ldquo;You shall call your walls Salvation and your gates Praise&rdquo; (Isa 60:18).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Hezekiah assembles the commanders in the city gate square and speaks to the people. As a type, the king&rsquo;s pre-battle address in the city square echoes the prophetic-royal preaching pattern. Christ&rsquo;s own pre-passion addresses to his disciples (John 14-17) are the fulfillment of this pattern: the king speaking courage and divine assurance to his people before the ultimate battle.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Be strong and courageous. Do not be afraid or dismayed before the king of Assyria and all the horde with him, for there is one greater with us than with him.&rdquo; The Deuteronomic formula of courage (<em>ḥizqû wĕʾimṣû</em>) was given first to Joshua and is now echoed by Hezekiah. As a type, the king who speaks courage to God&rsquo;s people before the overwhelming enemy prefigures Christ&rsquo;s words before his passion: &ldquo;In the world you will have tribulation. But take heart; I have overcome the world&rdquo; (John 16:33). &ldquo;There is one greater with us&rdquo; is the Emmanuel declaration in military form.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;With him is an arm of flesh, but with us is the LORD our God to help us and to fight our battles.&rdquo; This is the Emmanuel principle in its starkest form: human military power (&ldquo;arm of flesh&rdquo;) versus divine presence. As a direct type of Christ, this verse establishes the contrast that Matthew announces in naming Jesus &ldquo;Emmanuel (which means, God with us)&rdquo; (Matt 1:23). The LORD who fights for his people in 2 Chr 32 is the same God who, in Christ, fights and wins the ultimate battle against sin, death, and the devil &mdash; not with an arm of flesh but with the cross.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Sennacherib sends envoys to undermine Hezekiah&rsquo;s position while he himself remains at Lachish. As a theme, the enemy attacking the covenant people through representatives while the ruler directs the assault from a distance echoes the NT&rsquo;s portrait of spiritual warfare: the adversary &ldquo;prowls around like a roaring lion&rdquo; (1 Pet 5:8), operating through human agents to undermine faith in God&rsquo;s people.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Sennacherib&rsquo;s taunting question &mdash; &ldquo;On what are you relying?&rdquo; &mdash; is the enemy&rsquo;s foundational challenge to faith. As a theme, this question echoes through Scripture as the adversary&rsquo;s persistent attack on the ground of the believer&rsquo;s confidence. Satan&rsquo;s wilderness temptations of Jesus follow the same structure: &ldquo;If you are the Son of God&hellip;&rdquo; (Matt 4:3,6) &mdash; a challenge to the ground of identity and trust. Christ answers not with Hezekiah&rsquo;s political defense but with Scripture alone.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The accusation that Hezekiah is deceiving the people into death by claiming YHWH will deliver is an attempt to turn Judah&rsquo;s trust in their king into the cause of their doom. As a theme, the enemy&rsquo;s strategy of reframing trust in God&rsquo;s anointed as a death trap anticipates the mockery at the cross: &ldquo;He trusts in God; let God deliver him now, if he desires him&rdquo; (Matt 27:43). The taunt is structurally identical &mdash; both target the relationship between God and his anointed.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Sennacherib argues that Hezekiah insulted YHWH by removing his high places. As a theme, the accusation that the faithful king has actually offended God echoes the charge brought against Christ by the religious authorities: that his works were demonic (Matt 12:24), his words blasphemous (Matt 26:65). In both cases, the adversary attempts to weaponize religious tradition against YHWH&rsquo;s genuine representative.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Were the gods of those nations able to deliver their lands from me?&rdquo; Sennacherib lists his conquests as proof that YHWH cannot resist him. As a theme, the claim that past conquests prove divine impotence is the adversary&rsquo;s greatest error &mdash; it is precisely what YHWH refutes by raising Christ from the dead. Death, sin, and the law seemed to conquer &mdash; the cross looked like Sennacherib&rsquo;s victory over another god. The resurrection is the divine answer that no one could predict from the record of prior human defeats.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Who among all the gods of those nations was able to deliver?&rdquo; The rhetorical question assumes YHWH is merely one contestant among many. As a revelation of God, this verse sets up the great prophetic counter-claim of Isaiah 40-48: YHWH is not one deity among many but the creator of all nations, before whom the other gods are &ldquo;nothing&rdquo; (Isa 41:24). Christ embodies this divine singularity: &ldquo;There is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved&rdquo; (Acts 4:12).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Do not let Hezekiah deceive or mislead you.&rdquo; The enemy&rsquo;s final appeal is to suspicion of the anointed king himself. As a theme, the charge that the messianic figure is a deceiver runs from Sennacherib through Jeremiah&rsquo;s accusers (&ldquo;this man is deceiving us,&rdquo; Jer 38:4), to the charge against Jesus (&ldquo;he is leading the people astray,&rdquo; John 7:12), to the prediction that false christs will deceive many (Matt 24:24). The genuine Christ endures the accusation of deception because he alone speaks the truth.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The servants compound the blasphemy against both YHWH and Hezekiah. As a theme, the institutional reinforcement of blasphemy &mdash; officials multiplying the accusation of their master &mdash; anticipates the institutional rejection of Christ: the chief priests, scribes, and elders all joining to condemn (Matt 26:57-68). The corporate rejection of God&rsquo;s anointed follows this pattern of escalating institutional condemnation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The written letters equating YHWH with the gods of the nations are the most formal expression of the blasphemy. As a theme, the claim that YHWH is no different from defeated gods is what the NT calls the ultimate lie &mdash; the satanic inversion that presents the God of resurrection as just one power among many that can be defeated. Christ&rsquo;s resurrection permanently refutes this: &ldquo;He has been declared to be the Son of God in power by his resurrection from the dead&rdquo; (Rom 1:4).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Judean-language propaganda to demoralize the defenders. As a theme, the enemy speaking in the language of the covenant people to undermine their faith is a recurring strategy. The NT equivalent is false teaching that uses biblical language to undermine biblical faith: &ldquo;false prophets who come to you in sheep&rsquo;s clothing&rdquo; (Matt 7:15). Christ warns his own to test the spirits (1 John 4:1).</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;They spoke against the God of Jerusalem as they would speak against the gods of the peoples of the earth, which are the work of human hands.&rdquo; The equation of YHWH with manufactured gods is the foundational error. As a revelation of God, the distinction between YHWH and &ldquo;the work of human hands&rdquo; is absolute: YHWH is not made; he is the Maker. Christ embodies this distinction: &ldquo;All things were made through him, and without him was not anything made that was made&rdquo; (John 1:3). No human-made god can save; only the creator-God can.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;King Hezekiah and the prophet Isaiah son of Amoz prayed and cried out to heaven.&rdquo; The royal-prophetic prayer partnership at the moment of greatest threat is the decisive act. As a type, the king and prophet together appealing to YHWH prefigures Christ&rsquo;s own high-priestly prayer in John 17 &mdash; the Son appealing to the Father on behalf of his people, specifically at the moment of maximum opposition. Prayer is the act by which the covenant is activated in the crisis.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD sent an angel who struck down every mighty warrior, commander, and officer in the camp of the king of Assyria.&rdquo; As a type, the divine warrior acting through an angelic agent to destroy the enemy of God&rsquo;s anointed prefigures the eschatological judgment: at the parousia, Christ returns with the armies of heaven (Rev 19:14) and his enemies are struck down. Sennacherib&rsquo;s death &ldquo;by the sword of his own sons&rdquo; in the house of his own god is the ironic reversal: destroyed in the very sanctuary he thought would protect him.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD saved Hezekiah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem from the hand of Sennacherib.&rdquo; The triple statement of YHWH&rsquo;s saving act points to the comprehensive scope of divine deliverance. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes the character of YHWH as Savior &mdash; the attribute that reaches its fullest expression in the name of Jesus: <em>Yēšûaʿ</em> (YHWH saves). The deliverance of Jerusalem from Sennacherib is a temporal instance of the eternal salvation Christ accomplishes.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The nations bringing gifts to the LORD and to Hezekiah after the deliverance. As a theme, the Gentile tribute following divine victory over the enemy of God&rsquo;s anointed is the recurring pattern: Solomon received tribute (2 Chr 9), the Magi bring gifts to the infant Christ (Matt 2:1-12), and ultimately the kings of the earth bring their glory into the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:24-26). Each instance is a partial fulfillment of the Psalmic vision: &ldquo;All kings shall fall down before him; all nations shall serve him&rdquo; (Ps 72:11).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s mortal illness and his prayer. As a type, the faithful king facing death and crying out to God in prayer &mdash; and receiving a sign of extended life &mdash; is the pattern of Psalm 22 (the royal lament from the depths that ends in deliverance and universal praise). More directly, it anticipates Christ&rsquo;s Gethsemane prayer &mdash; &ldquo;he offered up prayers and supplications, with loud crying and tears, to him who was able to save him from death&rdquo; (Heb 5:7). The difference: Christ&rsquo;s prayer did not result in extended life but in resurrection through death.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;Hezekiah did not respond in proportion to the benefit he had received, for his heart was proud.&rdquo; The failure of gratitude after grace &mdash; pride following blessing &mdash; is the recurring human failure. As a revelation of God, Hezekiah&rsquo;s pride-after-deliverance is the very thing Christ comes to address: the human tendency to receive God&rsquo;s gifts and turn inward with self-congratulation. Christ himself is the anti-type of this pride: &ldquo;He humbled himself and became obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross&rdquo; (Phil 2:8).</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;Hezekiah humbled himself (<em>wayyikkānaʿ</em>) for the pride of his heart&hellip; so the LORD&rsquo;s wrath did not come upon them in the days of Hezekiah.&rdquo; The humility that averts divine wrath is the OT instance of the principle Paul articulates in connection with Christ: &ldquo;God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble&rdquo; (Jas 4:6; 1 Pet 5:5, quoting Prov 3:34). Christ perfectly embodies the humility that averts wrath not just for one individual but for all: his self-humbling at the cross absorbs the wrath that the proud cannot escape.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s great wealth and honor. As a theme, the covenantal blessing of wealth and honor given to the faithful king is the temporal shadow of the eschatological inheritance of Christ: &ldquo;He is the heir of all things&rdquo; (Heb 1:2), and those united to him share in his inheritance (Rom 8:17). The treasure-building of earthly kings points to the one who says, &ldquo;Do not lay up for yourselves treasures on earth&hellip; lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven&rdquo; (Matt 6:19-20).</p>",
    "28": "<p>Storehouses for grain, wine, and oil; stalls for livestock. As a theme, the provision of the faithful king for his people&rsquo;s food and livelihood echoes the motif of the divine shepherd who provides pasture (Ps 23:2). Christ fulfills this as the one who feeds the five thousand (John 6:1-13) and who identifies himself as the bread of life (John 6:35): the true storehouse of sustenance for God&rsquo;s people.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;God had given him great possessions.&rdquo; The explicit attribution of wealth to divine gift rather than human achievement establishes the theology of stewardship that runs through both Testaments. As a revelation of God, every good gift comes from the Father of lights (Jas 1:17), and Christ is the one in whom &ldquo;all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden&rdquo; (Col 2:3): the ultimate gift given by the Father for the world&rsquo;s blessing.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s engineering of the Siloam Tunnel &mdash; bringing water into the city of David. As a shadow, the provision of water within the city anticipates Christ as the source of living water within the new Jerusalem: &ldquo;The angel showed me the river of the water of life, bright as crystal, flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb&rdquo; (Rev 22:1). Hezekiah channels physical water into Jerusalem; Christ channels the living water of the Spirit into the city of God forever.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;God left him to himself, in order to test him and to know all that was in his heart.&rdquo; The divine testing of the faithful king&rsquo;s heart is a motif that runs from Abraham (Gen 22:1: &ldquo;God tested Abraham&rdquo;) through Moses to the wilderness testing of Israel (Deut 8:2: &ldquo;that he might know what was in your heart&rdquo;). The difference with Christ: tested in every respect as we are, yet without sin (Heb 4:15). Hezekiah failed the test with the Babylonian envoys; Christ passed every test, including Gethsemane.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The reference to the &ldquo;vision of Isaiah the prophet&rdquo; as a source document connects Hezekiah&rsquo;s reign to the prophetic tradition that Christ fulfills. Isaiah&rsquo;s &ldquo;vision&rdquo; (Isa 1:1) encompasses all 66 chapters, including the Servant Songs and the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 53. The Chronicler&rsquo;s citation of Isaiah as the interpretive source for Hezekiah&rsquo;s reign places Hezekiah within the prophetic trajectory that ends in Christ.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Hezekiah is buried with honor in the upper tombs of David&rsquo;s sons, and &ldquo;all Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem honored him at his death.&rdquo; As a theme, the honored burial of the faithful Davidic king is the OT anticipation of the resurrection and enthronement of Christ: laid in a tomb, yes, but not with the dishonor of the wicked (Isa 53:9: &ldquo;he was with a rich man in his death&rdquo;). The body of the anointed king matters; his death is not the final word.</p>"
  },
  "33": {
    "1": "<p>Manasseh&rsquo;s fifty-five year reign &mdash; the longest in Judean history. The theological tension is acute: how does the LORD tolerate the worst king for the longest reign? The Chronicler&rsquo;s answer is the repentance narrative of vv11-13. As a revelation of God, Manasseh&rsquo;s reign teaches that divine patience has a purpose: &ldquo;The Lord is not slow about his promise&hellip; but is patient toward you, not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance&rdquo; (2 Pet 3:9).</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;He did what was evil in the sight of the LORD, according to the detestable practices of the nations.&rdquo; Manasseh&rsquo;s evil is defined by external standard &mdash; the practices of the dispossessed nations. As a revelation of God, this establishes that YHWH&rsquo;s moral standard is consistent: what required the nations&rsquo; dispossession requires the same response from Israel. The universality of God&rsquo;s moral standard reaches its fullest expression in Christ who comes &ldquo;not to abolish the Law but to fulfill it&rdquo; (Matt 5:17).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Manasseh rebuilds what Hezekiah destroyed: high places, Baal altars, Asherah poles, host-of-heaven worship. As a theme, the reversal of reform by the next generation is the OT&rsquo;s recurring pattern of apostasy. It establishes the need for a transformation deeper than institutional reform &mdash; the new heart and new spirit of Ezekiel 36:26 that Christ mediates through the Spirit. No external reform can secure obedience; only new birth can (John 3:3-8).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Altars inside the LORD&rsquo;s house itself. As a shadow, this prefigures the &ldquo;abomination of desolation&rdquo; (Dan 9:27; Matt 24:15): the ultimate desecration of the sacred space by the ultimate adversary. Jesus explicitly cites this prophetic-historical pattern when describing the end-times sacrilege that will occur in the holy place. Manasseh&rsquo;s altars in the temple are the historical type of which the abomination of desolation is the eschatological antitype.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Altars to the host of heaven in both courts of the temple. As a theme, the colonization of the entire temple complex by astral worship represents the full displacement of YHWH from his own dwelling. This is the absolute inverse of what the temple should be: YHWH filling the temple with his glory (2 Chr 5:14). Christ reclaims this by driving out those who have displaced worship (John 2:13-17) and by making himself the true temple (John 2:19-21): &ldquo;Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up.&rdquo;</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;He burned his sons as offerings in the Valley of Ben-Hinnom.&rdquo; The Valley of Ben-Hinnom &mdash; <em>Gê-Hinnōm</em> &mdash; contracted in later Hebrew to <em>Gehenna</em>, became in Second Temple Jewish eschatology the term for the place of ultimate judgment. Jesus uses this term for the judgment of the wicked (Matt 5:22, 29-30; 10:28; 23:33). The valley where children were burned alive in Manasseh&rsquo;s reign becomes the name for the final fire from which Christ came to save. This connection is not coincidental: Manasseh&rsquo;s Gehenna is the historical reality behind Jesus&rsquo;s eschatological warning.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The carved idol placed in the house of God &mdash; the temple where YHWH declared &ldquo;In this house and in Jerusalem I have chosen&hellip; I will put my name forever.&rdquo; As a shadow, this act prefigures the &ldquo;man of lawlessness&rdquo; who &ldquo;takes his seat in the temple of God, proclaiming himself to be God&rdquo; (2 Thess 2:4) &mdash; the eschatological culmination of the pattern Manasseh began. The <em>šēm</em> (name) of YHWH that the temple houses is the name above every name (Phil 2:9-10): every usurpation is temporary; Christ&rsquo;s name alone endures.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The conditional covenant promise: &ldquo;if only they are careful to do all that I have commanded them.&rdquo; As a revelation of God, the conditionality of the land promise is the OT&rsquo;s diagnosis of the human problem: the condition cannot be met. Israel&rsquo;s repeated failure to obey establishes the theological necessity of the new covenant in which Christ fulfills the condition on behalf of his people (2 Cor 1:20: &ldquo;All the promises of God find their Yes in him&rdquo;).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Manasseh led Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem astray, so that they did more evil than the nations.&rdquo; The superlative evil of Manasseh&rsquo;s influence on the whole people shows the corporate dimension of sin: a king&rsquo;s spiritual condition shapes the spiritual health of his kingdom. As a type, this establishes the principle that Paul articulates in Adam&rsquo;s case: &ldquo;One man&rsquo;s trespass led to condemnation for all&rdquo; (Rom 5:18). Christ as the new Adam reverses this: one man&rsquo;s obedience leads to justification for all who are in him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD spoke to Manasseh and his people, but they would not listen.&rdquo; The persistent prophetic word that falls on unresponsive ears is the OT pattern that Jesus names as the defining sin of Jerusalem: &ldquo;How often would I have gathered your children together&hellip; and you were not willing&rdquo; (Matt 23:37). The unwillingness to hear YHWH&rsquo;s voice is what Christ comes to address by writing the law on the heart (Heb 8:10; Jer 31:33): the new covenant replaces unwillingness to hear with a hearing heart.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Manasseh captured and taken to Babylon in hooks. As a type, the king taken captive by the enemy to a foreign land under divine judgment prefigures the exile that Christ reverses: he &ldquo;led captivity captive&rdquo; (Eph 4:8, quoting Ps 68:18), taking the enemy&rsquo;s own weapon &mdash; death, exile, bondage &mdash; and turning it against the captor. Manasseh&rsquo;s captivity is the low point from which his repentance rises; Christ&rsquo;s descent into death is the low point from which his resurrection rises.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;In his distress he sought the favor of the LORD his God and humbled himself greatly before the God of his fathers.&rdquo; Manasseh&rsquo;s repentance is the most striking in all of Chronicles. The worst king repents. As a type, this is the OT&rsquo;s closest anticipation of the Prodigal Son (Luke 15:11-24): the son who squanders everything, reaches the lowest point, &ldquo;comes to himself,&rdquo; and returns to his father. The father runs to meet the returning son: &ldquo;God was moved by his prayer and heard his plea&rdquo; (v13). The pattern of the father who receives the worst sinner is the same God revealed in Christ.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;God was moved by his entreaty and heard his plea and brought him back to Jerusalem to his kingdom. Then Manasseh knew that the LORD is God.&rdquo; The three movements &mdash; God moved, God heard, God restored &mdash; are the gospel pattern in OT dress. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes that divine responsiveness to repentance is not an NT innovation but YHWH&rsquo;s consistent character. Christ does not reveal a different God than the God of Manasseh&rsquo;s restoration &mdash; he reveals the same God more fully, showing that this restoration was purchased by the Son&rsquo;s own self-giving.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Manasseh builds an outer wall after his restoration. As a theme, the restored king immediately begins building &mdash; constructive action following repentance is the pattern of genuine transformation. The NT equivalent is Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;faith working through love&rdquo; (Gal 5:6): repentance produces fruit. The restored sinner does not merely return to a previous state but begins building what was previously neglected.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Manasseh removes the foreign gods and the idol from the temple and destroys all the altars he had built. As a type, the repentant king dismantling his own idolatrous work is the OT instance of what Paul calls &ldquo;putting to death the deeds of the body&rdquo; (Rom 8:13): the active destruction of what one has constructed against God. The thoroughness of the dismantling mirrors the thoroughness of the repentance.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Manasseh restores the altar of YHWH and offers peace offerings and thank offerings, commanding Judah to serve YHWH. As a type, the restored sinner becoming a witness to others is the NT pattern: the formerly demonized man sent to proclaim what Jesus did (Mark 5:19-20), the Samaritan woman who tells her village (John 4:28-29), Zacchaeus who restores fourfold what he took (Luke 19:8). Restoration produces testimony and generosity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;The people still sacrificed at the high places, though only to the LORD their God.&rdquo; The persistence of old patterns even after repentance &mdash; proper object, improper location &mdash; reflects the incompleteness of any OT reform. As a theme, the Chronicler&rsquo;s note of residual impurity even in the best situations points to the need for a reformation deeper than institutional change. The new covenant addresses this root: &ldquo;I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit within you&rdquo; (Ezek 36:26).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Reference to Manasseh&rsquo;s prayer and the words of the seers. As a revelation of God, the preservation of the memory of a repentant sinner&rsquo;s prayer is itself a theological statement: YHWH does not simply record the sins but also the prayers that address them. The deuterocanonical &ldquo;Prayer of Manasseh&rdquo; represents later generations&rsquo; recognition that this prayer mattered enough to reconstruct. Christ is the ultimate guarantor that the prayers of repentant sinners are preserved: he &ldquo;always lives to make intercession for them&rdquo; (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The full record: Manasseh&rsquo;s prayer, God&rsquo;s reception of it, all his sins and unfaithfulness, and the sites of his idolatry before he humbled himself. As a revelation of God, the comprehensive record that includes both the sin and the repentance establishes the divine economy: nothing is hidden, but nothing is beyond the reach of the divine response to humility. This is the theology of the final judgment as Paul describes it: &ldquo;God will bring every deed into judgment&rdquo; (Eccl 12:14) &mdash; but in Christ, the judgment is borne by the Son so that those who humble themselves stand forgiven.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Manasseh dies and is buried in his own house. The Chronicler records no ceremony of public honor &mdash; the ambiguity of his legacy remains. As a theme, the absence of the full burial honor for Manasseh reflects the partial and mixed nature of his reign: remarkable repentance but too much damage done. This points to the need for a king whose reign is unambiguously faithful from beginning to end &mdash; which no son of David achieves until Christ.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Amon&rsquo;s two-year reign. As a theme, the brief reign of the apostate son follows the pattern of sudden truncation for those who persist in rebellion against YHWH&rsquo;s covenant. The brevity of Amon&rsquo;s reign is itself a theological message: the anti-Davidic king cannot sustain his position. In contrast, Christ&rsquo;s kingdom &ldquo;shall have no end&rdquo; (Luke 1:33) because his faithfulness is unbroken.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Amon sacrificed to the same idols his father had made before his repentance. As a theme, the selective inheritance &mdash; taking the sin but not the repentance &mdash; represents the human tendency to choose the easier path. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes that repentance cannot be inherited; it must be personally appropriated. The NT equivalent: &ldquo;Do not think you can say to yourselves, &lsquo;We have Abraham as our father&rsquo;&rdquo; (Matt 3:9). Each person must repent and believe.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;He did not humble himself before the LORD as his father Manasseh had humbled himself, but Amon incurred more and more guilt.&rdquo; The deliberate contrast with Manasseh makes Amon&rsquo;s refusal the more culpable: he knew what repentance looked like and refused it. As a revelation of God, the one who has seen repentance modeled and refuses it bears greater guilt &mdash; a principle Christ articulates in the judgment of Chorazin and Bethsaida (Matt 11:21-22): greater light brings greater judgment if rejected.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Amon is assassinated by his own servants. As a theme, the king destroyed by those within his own household echoes the pattern of betrayal by intimates that culminates in Judas&rsquo;s betrayal of Christ. The inside betrayal of the anointed &mdash; or the one who should have been faithful &mdash; is a recurring motif (Ps 41:9: &ldquo;Even my close friend in whom I trusted, who ate my bread, has lifted his heel against me&rdquo;; John 13:18).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;The people of the land struck down all who had conspired against King Amon and made his son Josiah king.&rdquo; The popular vindication of the Davidic line &mdash; the common people installing the heir &mdash; is a covenant act: the people refusing to let the Davidic dynasty fall to conspiracy. As a shadow, this popular vindication of the Davidic heir anticipates the crowds who welcome Jesus into Jerusalem (Matt 21:8-9) and who will form the nucleus of the messianic people, even as the elites plot his death.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "1": "<p>Josiah is eight years old at accession. As a type, the young king who will prove to be the last great faithful Davidic ruler before the exile is a foreshadowing of the one who, as a twelve-year-old, was already &ldquo;about his Father&rsquo;s business&rdquo; in the temple (Luke 2:49). Both are young men whose commitment to YHWH is evident before the world expects it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;He did what was right in the sight of the LORD, walking in the ways of his ancestor David and not turning aside to the right or to the left.&rdquo; The Deuteronomic formula of perfect obedience (&ldquo;not turning aside to right or left&rdquo;) is used of the ideal Deuteronomic king (Deut 17:20; Josh 1:7). No Davidic king fully embodies this ideal &mdash; the formula describes what they should be. Christ perfectly embodies it: &ldquo;He committed no sin, neither was deceit found in his mouth&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:22; Isa 53:9).</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;In the eighth year of his reign, while still young, he began to seek (<em>dāraš</em>) the God of his ancestor David.&rdquo; As a type, the young king beginning to seek God before the visible reform starts anticipates the boy Jesus in the temple: the divine Son already occupied with his Father&rsquo;s house before his public ministry (Luke 2:41-52). Both begin their decisive engagement with God&rsquo;s purposes at a young age. The dāraš (seeking) that the Chronicler tracks through the Davidic kings finds its ultimate expression in Christ, who is both the seeker and the one sought (Luke 19:10: &ldquo;The Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost&rdquo;).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The demolition of Baal altars in Josiah&rsquo;s presence &mdash; the king personally overseeing the destruction of false worship. As a type, the anointed king driving out idolatry from the covenant people&rsquo;s land anticipates Christ&rsquo;s temple cleansing (John 2:13-17; Matt 21:12-13): &ldquo;Zeal for your house has consumed me&rdquo; (John 2:17, quoting Ps 69:9). The holy zeal of the anointed king against that which defiles the Father&rsquo;s house runs from Josiah to Christ.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Burning the bones of idolatrous priests on their own altars permanently defiles those altars against future use. As a type, the radical, irreversible dismantling of the cult apparatus by the faithful king points to Christ&rsquo;s own irreversible act: his once-for-all sacrifice (Heb 10:12-14) permanently dismantles the need for any further sacrifice. &ldquo;Where there is forgiveness of these, there is no longer any offering for sin&rdquo; (Heb 10:18).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The reform extends into the northern territories. As a theme, the pan-Israelite scope of Josiah&rsquo;s reform anticipates the eschatological reunion of all Israel that the prophets project: &ldquo;I will take the stick of Joseph&hellip; and join it with the stick of Judah&rdquo; (Ezek 37:19). Christ&rsquo;s mission is explicitly pan-Israelite before it extends to the Gentiles: &ldquo;I was sent only to the lost sheep of the house of Israel&rdquo; (Matt 15:24), and Paul sees in Christ the &ldquo;one new man in place of the two&rdquo; (Eph 2:15).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The comprehensive vocabulary of destruction applied to every idol &mdash; cut down, ground to powder, demolished throughout all Israel. As a shadow, the total annihilation of the idol-cult by the faithful king prefigures Christ&rsquo;s final destruction of every anti-God power: &ldquo;He must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet. The last enemy to be destroyed is death&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:25-26). The comprehensiveness of Josiah&rsquo;s reform is the OT shadow of the comprehensiveness of Christ&rsquo;s eschatological victory.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Josiah initiates the temple repair in his eighteenth year. As a theme, the king who purges the land and then turns to repair the house of God establishes the sequence that matters: external idolatry is addressed before the internal sanctuary. As a revelation of God, this sequence points to Christ&rsquo;s order of priorities: the temple must be cleansed (John 2) before the temple can become what it was meant to be &mdash; a house of prayer for all nations (Mark 11:17).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The temple-tax money gathered from Manasseh, Ephraim, all the remnant of Israel, and all Judah and Benjamin. As a theme, the pan-Israelite contribution to the temple repair represents a renewed covenant solidarity: scattered Israel gathering its resources around the house of YHWH. This anticipates the NT image of the church as a spiritual house built from living stones &ldquo;from every tribe and language and people and nation&rdquo; (Rev 5:9) &mdash; the true pan-Israelite temple that Christ builds.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The money entrusted to workmen who oversee the LORD&rsquo;s house, specifically those &ldquo;who work faithfully.&rdquo; As a theme, faithful stewardship of resources entrusted for the building of God&rsquo;s house is the OT instance of the parable of the talents (Matt 25:14-30): those who work faithfully with what has been entrusted are praised; the house is built by faithful labor with the Master&rsquo;s resources.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;To provide for the buildings that the kings of Judah had neglected.&rdquo; As a theme, the restoration of what prior unfaithfulness had allowed to decay is the work of the faithful king. Christ comes to restore what the long history of human unfaithfulness has broken: &ldquo;I will restore to you the years that the swarming locust has eaten&rdquo; (Joel 2:25). Every act of temple repair in the OT is a shadow of the ultimate restoration that Christ brings.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Levites faithfully supervise the construction work. As a theme, the proper Levitical oversight of the temple economy &mdash; the priestly intermediaries ensuring the work is done rightly &mdash; is the OT form of what the NT describes as the church&rsquo;s leadership: those appointed to oversee the building of God&rsquo;s spiritual house (Eph 4:11-12), equipping the saints for the work of ministry so that the body is built up.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Levites serve as supervisors of burden-bearers and directors of all workers, with scribes and officials and gatekeepers also involved. As a theme, the organized administrative structure of the temple-building project reflects the divine order of the covenant community. Paul&rsquo;s description of the body with many members each functioning in their role (1 Cor 12:12-27) is the NT form of this cooperative building structure under divine oversight.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Hilkiah the priest found the book of the law of the LORD given through Moses.&rdquo; As a shadow pointing toward Christ, the discovery of the lost Word of God in the temple is one of the most theologically freighted events in the OT. The Word was present all along but unrecognized, housed in the physical structure of the temple. John 1:14 &mdash; &ldquo;The Word became flesh and dwelt (<em>eskēnōsen</em> &mdash; tabernacled) among us&rdquo; &mdash; is the NT fulfillment: the Word is no longer a scroll hidden in the temple but the living Son present among his people. The book that was found in the house of God becomes the God who dwells in the house of his people.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Hilkiah&rsquo;s announcement &mdash; &ldquo;I have found the book of the law.&rdquo; As a theme, the finding of the lost Word that transforms a kingdom resonates with the parables of the lost sheep, lost coin, and lost son (Luke 15): what was lost is found, and joy follows. The nation&rsquo;s response to the found book (tearing clothes, seeking the LORD) is the appropriate response to finding the Word &mdash; the same response that genuine hearing of the gospel produces.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Shaphan brings the book to the king and reads it aloud. As a theme, the reading of the Word of God before the king &mdash; the representative of the covenant people &mdash; is the public proclamation of the law that the Deuteronomic king was supposed to read daily (Deut 17:18-19). The reading that produces transformation is what James calls being &ldquo;doers of the word and not hearers only&rdquo; (Jas 1:22): Josiah hears and acts. This is precisely the posture toward the Word that Christ calls his hearers to (Luke 8:21: &ldquo;My mother and brothers are those who hear the word of God and do it&rdquo;).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The accountable reporting of the money collected and distributed. As a theme, the transparent stewardship of resources in the service of God&rsquo;s house reflects the accountability that Christ builds into his kingdom: &ldquo;From everyone who has been given much, much will be required&rdquo; (Luke 12:48). The accounting of resources for the temple is a shadow of the final accounting before the one who knows all stewardship.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Shaphan reads the book before the king. As a revelation of God, the moment when the Word of God is read and received by the covenant people&rsquo;s representative is a salvific moment. Christ himself reads the scripture in the Nazareth synagogue and declares, &ldquo;Today this scripture has been fulfilled in your hearing&rdquo; (Luke 4:21): the Word of God read and the Word incarnate speaking are the same Word, now present in person.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;When the king heard the words of the law, he tore his clothes.&rdquo; As a type, the king whose heart is broken by the Word of God contrasts sharply with Jehoiakim (Jer 36:23-24) who cuts the scroll and throws it in the fire. Josiah&rsquo;s torn clothes are the physical enactment of the &ldquo;broken and contrite heart&rdquo; that God does not despise (Ps 51:17). Christ himself is moved to tears at the hardness of Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) &mdash; the opposite of Jehoiakim, the anti-Josiah.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The delegation sent to inquire of the LORD. As a theme, the king who does not presume to interpret the Word on his own but seeks prophetic guidance reflects the epistemic humility that Christ commends: &ldquo;Apart from me you can do nothing&rdquo; (John 15:5). Josiah has the text but seeks the living prophetic voice that interprets it. The NT equivalent is the Spirit who &ldquo;will guide you into all the truth&rdquo; (John 16:13).</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Great is the wrath of the LORD that is poured out on us because our fathers have not kept the word of the LORD.&rdquo; Josiah&rsquo;s diagnosis is precise: the accumulated debt of covenant unfaithfulness has created a judicial situation that must be addressed. As a revelation of God, this verse captures the diagnosis of the human condition that the gospel addresses: &ldquo;The wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all ungodliness and unrighteousness&rdquo; (Rom 1:18). Christ comes to bear this wrath on behalf of those who cannot bear it themselves.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The delegation goes to Huldah the prophetess. As a revelation of God, the fact that YHWH&rsquo;s word comes through a woman prophet &mdash; when male prophets are also available &mdash; establishes the principle that prophetic authority is not determined by gender but by YHWH&rsquo;s choice. In the new covenant, the Spirit is poured out on &ldquo;your sons and your daughters&rdquo; (Acts 2:17), removing the gender restriction on prophetic witness. Huldah is an OT anticipation of this new-covenant reality.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;Thus says the LORD, the God of Israel.&rdquo; The messenger formula establishing Huldah&rsquo;s prophetic authority is the same formula used by every true prophet from Moses to Malachi. As a revelation of God, the consistent use of this formula across the OT establishes the coherence of the prophetic word: one God speaking through many voices. Christ fulfills this by being not merely the messenger but the message: &ldquo;In many and various ways God spoke&hellip; but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&rdquo; (Heb 1:1-2).</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;I will bring disaster upon this place and upon its inhabitants &mdash; all the curses written in the book.&rdquo; The Deuteronomic curse-fulfillment mechanism: the covenantal consequences of disobedience, written in advance, are now activated. As a revelation of God, this verse establishes that divine judgment is not arbitrary but covenantal: it follows the terms announced at Sinai. Christ bears precisely these curses on behalf of his people: &ldquo;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&rdquo; (Gal 3:13).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;Because they have abandoned me and made offerings to other gods&hellip; my wrath will be poured out on this place and will not be quenched.&rdquo; The unquenchable wrath corresponds to the unquenchable fire of Gehenna that Jesus uses as the image of final judgment (Mark 9:43). The wrath that will not be quenched in Jerusalem&rsquo;s history (fulfilled in 586 BCE) is the OT form of what the NT presents as the eschatological wrath from which Christ saves those who believe (Rom 5:9; 1 Thess 1:10).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The second oracle &mdash; addressed to Josiah personally &mdash; distinguishes corporate judgment from individual mercy. As a revelation of God, this structural distinction in Huldah&rsquo;s two-part oracle establishes a principle that Christ himself articulates: the judgment on the nation (Jerusalem will fall) and the mercy for the believing individual (those who flee to the mountains will be saved, Matt 24:16-18) are both real and must not be collapsed into each other.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;Because your heart was tender and you humbled yourself before God when you heard his words against this place and its inhabitants, and you humbled yourself before me and tore your clothes and wept before me, I have heard you.&rdquo; The hearing of YHWH follows the tearing of the heart. As a revelation of God, this verse is a condensed version of the gospel: the broken and contrite heart does not go unheard. Christ himself &ldquo;offered up prayers and supplications, with loud crying and tears&rdquo; and &ldquo;was heard because of his reverence&rdquo; (Heb 5:7). The tender-hearted king who weeps before God finds YHWH listening &mdash; and so does the High Priest who weeps in Gethsemane.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;Your eyes shall not see all the disaster that I will bring upon this place.&rdquo; Josiah is spared the sight of Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall by a merciful death. As a type, this mercy-within-judgment echoes Simeon&rsquo;s blessing: &ldquo;Lord, now you let your servant depart in peace, for my eyes have seen your salvation&rdquo; (Luke 2:29-30). Both are faithful covenant servants granted peace in their death before the judgment falls. The difference: Simeon has seen the salvation that Josiah only hoped for.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Josiah summons the elders of Judah and Jerusalem for the covenant renewal. As a type, the anointed king assembling the whole people before the Word of God for covenant renewal anticipates the Last Supper: Christ assembling his disciples to establish the new covenant in his blood (Matt 26:26-28). Both are the king&rsquo;s covenant assembly at a pivotal moment before his own death.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The reading of the covenant book &ldquo;in the hearing&rdquo; of the whole assembly &mdash; men, women, children, priests, Levites. As a type, the public reading of the Word before the covenant people assembled anticipates Paul&rsquo;s instructions: &ldquo;When this letter has been read among you, have it also read in the church of the Laodiceans&rdquo; (Col 4:16). The hearing of God&rsquo;s word by the entire gathered community is the constitutive act of the covenant people from Sinai through Josiah to the church.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;The king stood in his place and made a covenant before the LORD, to follow the LORD and keep his commandments&hellip; with all his heart and all his soul.&rdquo; The full Shema-love formula in a covenant-making context. As a type, the Davidic king making covenant with YHWH on behalf of the people is the pattern that Christ fulfills: he is the covenant himself (Isa 42:6: &ldquo;I will give you as a covenant for the people&rdquo;), the one who gives his life as the covenant-sealing sacrifice (Heb 9:15: &ldquo;he is the mediator of a new covenant, so that those who are called may receive the promised eternal inheritance&rdquo;).</p>",
    "32": "<p>Josiah requires all who were present to stand to the covenant. As a theme, the corporate binding to the covenant by the faithful king on behalf of the whole people anticipates the work of Christ as the one who establishes the new covenant obligation on behalf of all who are in him. In Christ, the covenant is no longer merely imposed from outside but fulfilled from within by the one who &ldquo;through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God&rdquo; (Heb 9:14).</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;Josiah removed all the abominations from all the territories belonging to the people of Israel and required all who were present in Israel to serve the LORD their God. All his days they did not turn aside from following the LORD.&rdquo; The Chronicler&rsquo;s closing evaluation of Josiah is unqualified: under this king, the covenant was fully kept. This is the highest point of the Davidic dynasty before its fall. As a type, Josiah&rsquo;s reign of total covenant faithfulness is the OT&rsquo;s closest anticipation of what Christ permanently establishes: the eternal kingdom in which the people of God &ldquo;will serve him day and night in his temple&rdquo; (Rev 7:15), never again turning aside from following the LORD their God.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRON2)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRON2.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 32-34')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
